---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const title = "5 Common Mistakes When Counting Calories | SmartFitCalc";
const description =
    "Avoid these common calorie counting errors that prevent weight loss progress. Learn how to track accurately.";

const articleStructuredData = {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    headline: "5 Common Mistakes When Counting Calories",
    description: description,
    datePublished: "2024-12-01",
    dateModified: "2025-12-28",
    author: {
        "@type": "Organization",
        name: "SmartFitCalc",
        url: "https://smartfitcalc.com",
    },
    publisher: {
        "@type": "Organization",
        name: "SmartFitCalc",
        url: "https://smartfitcalc.com",
        logo: {
            "@type": "ImageObject",
            url: "https://smartfitcalc.com/favicon.svg",
        },
    },
    mainEntityOfPage: {
        "@type": "WebPage",
        "@id": "https://smartfitcalc.com/blog/calorie-counting-mistakes",
    },
};
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
    <script
        type="application/ld+json"
        set:html={JSON.stringify(articleStructuredData)}
    />
    <article class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
        <header class="mb-10 text-center">
            <a href="/blog" class="text-sm text-primary-600 hover:underline"
                >← Back to Blog</a
            >
            <h1 class="mt-4 mb-4 text-4xl font-extrabold text-gray-800">
                5 Common Mistakes When Counting Calories
            </h1>
            <div class="text-gray-500 text-sm">December 2024 • 5 min read</div>
        </header>

        <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-gray-600">
            <p class="lead text-xl">
                "I'm eating 1,500 calories but not losing weight!" Sound
                familiar? Chances are, one of these mistakes is the culprit.
                Here's how to count calories accurately.
            </p>

            <div class="rounded-xl bg-red-50 p-5 my-6 border border-red-100">
                <h3 class="font-bold text-red-800 mb-2">
                    Mistake #1: Eyeballing Portions
                </h3>
                <p class="text-red-700">
                    Studies show people underestimate portions by 30-50%. That
                    "tablespoon" of peanut butter might actually be three. A
                    food scale is a $20 investment that pays dividends.
                </p>
                <p class="text-red-600 text-sm mt-3 font-medium">
                    Fix: Weigh everything (at least initially) to learn what
                    portions really look like.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div
                class="rounded-xl bg-orange-50 p-5 my-6 border border-orange-100"
            >
                <h3 class="font-bold text-orange-800 mb-2">
                    Mistake #2: Forgetting Cooking Oils and Sauces
                </h3>
                <p class="text-orange-700">
                    A tablespoon of olive oil is 120 calories. Ranch dressing
                    adds 150 per serving. These "invisible" calories accumulate
                    fast.
                </p>
                <p class="text-orange-600 text-sm mt-3 font-medium">
                    Fix: Log everything—oils, butter, dressings, condiments, and
                    cooking sprays.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div
                class="rounded-xl bg-yellow-50 p-5 my-6 border border-yellow-100"
            >
                <h3 class="font-bold text-yellow-800 mb-2">
                    Mistake #3: Not Logging BLTs (Bites, Licks, Tastes)
                </h3>
                <p class="text-yellow-700">
                    That handful of chips, the bite of your partner's pasta,
                    tasting while cooking—these add up. Even 200-300 untracked
                    calories daily can stall progress.
                </p>
                <p class="text-yellow-600 text-sm mt-3 font-medium">
                    Fix: Log everything immediately, even small tastes. Use a
                    "miscellaneous" entry if needed.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="rounded-xl bg-blue-50 p-5 my-6 border border-blue-100">
                <h3 class="font-bold text-blue-800 mb-2">
                    Mistake #4: Trusting Restaurant Calculations
                </h3>
                <p class="text-blue-700">
                    Restaurant portions often exceed listed calories by 20-30%.
                    Chefs don't measure ingredients precisely, and extra oil or
                    butter is common.
                </p>
                <p class="text-blue-600 text-sm mt-3 font-medium">
                    Fix: Add 20% to restaurant calorie counts as a buffer, or
                    eat at home more often.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div
                class="rounded-xl bg-purple-50 p-5 my-6 border border-purple-100"
            >
                <h3 class="font-bold text-purple-800 mb-2">
                    Mistake #5: Weekend Amnesia
                </h3>
                <p class="text-purple-700">
                    Strict tracking Monday-Friday but relaxing on weekends? Two
                    days of overeating can erase a week's deficit. A 3,000
                    calorie Saturday undoes 5 days at a 500-calorie deficit.
                </p>
                <p class="text-purple-600 text-sm mt-3 font-medium">
                    Fix: Track every day, or use weekly calorie averages to
                    account for social eating.
                </p>
            </div>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-4">
                The Accuracy Mindset
            </h2>
            <p>
                The goal isn't perfection—it's awareness. Even if your tracking
                isn't perfect, consistent tracking reveals patterns. You'll
                learn which foods are calorie-dense, which meals keep you full,
                and where your weak spots are.
            </p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-4">
                Quick Accuracy Tips
            </h2>
            <ul>
                <li>Use a food scale for solid foods</li>
                <li>Measure liquids with measuring cups</li>
                <li>Log before you eat, not after</li>
                <li>Use verified entries in food databases</li>
                <li>When unsure, round up</li>
            </ul>

            <p class="mt-8">
                Know your calorie needs first? <a
                    href="/"
                    class="text-primary-600 hover:underline font-medium"
                    >Calculate your TDEE →</a
                >
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="mt-12 pt-8 border-t border-gray-200">
            <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-800 mb-4">Related Articles</h3>
            <div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2">
                <a
                    href="/blog/calculate-macros-weight-loss"
                    class="block rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-4 hover:border-primary-300"
                >
                    <h4 class="font-medium text-gray-800">
                        Calculate Macros for Weight Loss
                    </h4>
                    <p class="text-sm text-gray-500">Beyond just calories</p>
                </a>
                <a
                    href="/blog/understanding-tdee"
                    class="block rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-4 hover:border-primary-300"
                >
                    <h4 class="font-medium text-gray-800">
                        Understanding TDEE
                    </h4>
                    <p class="text-sm text-gray-500">Your calorie baseline</p>
                </a>
            </div>
        </div>
    </article>
</BaseLayout>
